Version Control Systems fall in two category
Centralized
Distributed

In centralized system, all team member connect to a central system
to get the latest copy of the code and to share changes to each other
like "subversion" & "Microsoft Team Foundation Server" are centralized version control systems.
the problem is, the SINGLE POINT OF FAILURE.
if server down, we can not collaborate or save snapshots. (we should wait!)


In distributed systems, we have not this problem!
every team member has a copy of the project and history,
the code is not limited to specific server!
we can save snapshots locally on our machines.
if the central server is offline (git.com)
we can synchronize our work directly to others.
like "Git" & "Mercurial"


Note: we have some GUI tools for using git
      like "GitKraken" & "Sourcetree"
      but we use terminal in the course most of the times!


Note: if we install Git on windows,
      we will have "Git BASH"
      BASH: Born Again SHEll,
      its a command prompt window, that simulate Unix or Linux environments.